# Executive Summary

## Business Context

Amazon observed a significant decline in Repeat Purchase Rate (RPR) among customers in Tier-1 cities.

| Quarter | Repeat Purchase Rate |
|----------|----------|
| Q1 | 52% |
| Q2 | 44% |
| Q3 | 34% |

The objective of this analysis was to identify the root cause behind the decline and recommend business actions to improve customer retention.

---

## Approach

The investigation followed a hypothesis-driven analytics framework.

### External Factors Evaluated

- Economic conditions
- Industry performance
- Seller and vendor ecosystem
- Competitive landscape
- Quick Commerce expansion
- Delivery competitiveness

### Internal Factors Evaluated

- Customer acquisition quality
- Customer engagement
- Delivery performance
- Product satisfaction
- Customer complaints
- Product returns
- Funnel behavior
- Cart abandonment
- Prime membership impact
- Customer demographics
- Product category trends

---

## Key Findings

### Customer Quality Remained Stable

Acquisition channels remained consistent across quarters.

No evidence suggested deterioration in customer quality.

---

### Customer Engagement Remained Stable

Users continued visiting the platform after their first purchase.

Customer activity rates remained consistent.

---

### Product Experience Remained Stable

Reviews, complaints and return rates remained largely unchanged.

No significant deterioration in customer satisfaction was observed.

---

### Customers Demonstrated Higher Purchase Intent

Users increasingly relied on direct search rather than casual browsing.

This suggests stronger purchase intent rather than weaker demand.

---

### Cart Abandonment Emerged as the Primary Problem Area

Search-to-cart conversion remained healthy.

However, customers increasingly abandoned their carts before purchase.

---

### Delivery Expectations Deteriorated

Non-repeat customers increasingly saw longer delivery promises.

Customers who continued purchasing consistently saw faster delivery estimates.

---

### Non-Prime Customers Drove Most of the Decline

The largest reduction in repeat purchases occurred among non-prime customers.

Prime membership appeared to protect against customer churn.

---

### Younger Customers Were Most Affected

More than 80% of affected customers belonged to the 18–34 age segment.

These customers also demonstrated very low Prime adoption.

---

### Quick Commerce Categories Were Most Impacted

The largest increase in abandonment occurred in:

- Beauty & Personal Care
- Grocery & Essentials
- Fashion
- Electronics Accessories

These categories overlap strongly with Quick Commerce demand.

---

## Root Cause

The decline in repeat purchases is primarily driven by changing customer expectations around delivery speed.

Quick Commerce platforms have fundamentally altered delivery expectations in Tier-1 cities.

Customers who previously accepted 3–4 day delivery increasingly expect:

- Same-day delivery
- Next-day delivery
- Instant fulfillment

The impact is strongest among:

- Younger customers
- Non-prime customers
- Tier-1 city users
- Quick Commerce dominated categories

---

## Recommendations

### Short-Term

- Increase Prime adoption
- Student-focused Prime promotions
- Improve warehouse placement
- Prioritize high-demand categories
- Expand same-day delivery coverage

### Long-Term

- Launch Quick Commerce operations
- Build hyperlocal fulfillment centers
- Expand dark-store network
- Improve inventory proximity

---

## Business Impact

Expected benefits include:

- Increased Repeat Purchase Rate
- Reduced Cart Abandonment
- Improved Customer Retention
- Higher Customer Lifetime Value
- Stronger Competitive Positioning
